 Laying out the features of the Law that eventually destroy K., Burns argues that the American criminal justice system has taken on many of these same features. In the overwhelming majority of contemporary cases, police interrogation is followed by a plea bargain, in which the court’s only function is to set a largely predetermined sentence for an individual already presumed guilty. Like Kafka’s nightmarish vision, much of American criminal law and procedure has become unknowable, ubiquitous, and bureaucratic. It, too, has come to rely on deception in dealing with suspects and jurors, to limit the role of defense, and to increasingly dispense justice without the protection of formal procedures. But, while Kennedy may be correct in his grim assessment, a remedy is available in the tradition of trial by jury, and Burns concludes by convincingly arguing for its return to a more central place in American criminal justice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofxUnited States. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzUnited States. 0aCriminal procedurexUnited States. 0aCriminal procedurezUnited States. 0aLaw in literature. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  acriminal justice, crime, legal, law, the trial, famous author, allegory, real life, prison, court system, police, plea bargain, sentencing, guilt, innocence, contemporary, modern, bureaucratic, bureaucracy, jury, juror, judge, institutional, equality, equity, inequality, conflict, reform, ethics, unethical, racism, literary, literature, analysis, college, university, academic, scholarship.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226167503423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226167503/original